I'm just getting started using the exabgp API so I'm open to any valid json encoding.  I don't have a strong opinion on which encoding might be better/worse yet.

I modelled the return type from json() to match what is returned for an ipv4/ipv6 unicast entry.  The [inet json() function](https://github.com/Exa-Networks/exabgp/blob/master/lib/exabgp/bgp/message/update/nlri/inet.py#L79) returns a wrapped dictionary, not just a name/value binding.  Now unicast and flow encodings are a list of dicts.  Prior to this, flow encoding was an (invalid) list containing a name:value pair.

If the flowspec encoding changes to a list of dictionaries without the ```"flow-%s":``` (as you've proposed), would you also want to change the ipv4/6 unicast encoding in a similar way drop the ```"nlri":```?  Seems good to have them use a similar encoding.

For reference, this is the encoding I see for ipv4 unicast:
```
...
				"announce": {
					"ipv4 unicast": {
						"127.0.0.1": [{
							"nlri": "10.2.0.0/16"
						}]
					}
				}
...
```

And with this commit, this is the encoding I see for ipv4 flow:
```
...
				"announce": {
					"ipv4 flow": {
						"no-nexthop": [{
							"flow-3": {
								"destination-ipv4": ["10.2.0.0/16"],
								"source-ipv4": ["10.2.0.0/16"],
								"protocol": ["=udp"],
								"string": "flow destination-ipv4 10.2.0.0/16 source-ipv4 10.2.0.0/16 protocol =udp"
							}
						}]
					}
				}
...
```

