    {
        GetSockName().mPort = static_cast<Udp *>(mTransport)->GetEphemeralPort();
    }
```

I figured out how to fix this.  A note in the docs alludes to the fact that for Python 2.7 `py::bytes` is returned as a `str` in Python.  Otherwise, a `unicode` object is returned instead of `str` which causes the exception.  The following code fixes the issue:

```
#include "pybind11_tests.h"

class TestHexType{};

TEST_SUBMODULE(test_hex, m) {
  py::class_<TestHexType>(m, "TestHexType")
    .def(py::init<>())
    .def("__hex__", [](const TestHexType &_){return py::bytes("0xDEADBEEF");});
}
```
I'm not sure if this means that a Python module supporting 2.7 and 3.x will need some conditional compilation to handle this case, but it's a possibility.

